Intro

This is a didactic experiment on basic data analysis with R, using the datasets downloaded from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control webpage: https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications-data/download-todays-data-geographic-distribution-covid-19-cases-worldwide

This is not a way to underestimate the suffering of this period.

Unfortunately every number here is a person that got sick or died, a tragedy. So I want to underline that this is not playing with numbers and colors but an attempt to help people to critically look at real data with a scientific perspective.

If you are not interested in learning R you can go directly to the “Total Cases” tab to have a look at the data. Or look at better sources like this one: https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6

Outside the emergency, our main activity is to study the physiology and pathology of neurodevelopment, in the lab of Giuseppe Testa at the European Institute of Oncology and the Human Technopole, University of Milan, Italy. You can read more here http://www.testalab.eu/bibliography/

SetUp

In this first chunck we start loading the libraries that contain the functions that will facilitate our work later

library(Hmisc)
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(learnr)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(plotly)
library(htmlwidgets)
data <-  read_excel("DataECDC/COVID-19-geographic-disbtribution-worldwide-2020-03-16.xls")

Numeric Variable Exploration

Scatterplot

The first kind of useful plot for looking at the data is a scatterplot between 2 numeric variables

ggplot(data, aes(x=NewConfCases, y=NewDeaths)) + geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

And you can use the boxplot function that shows you the distribution of your data points. By default it highlights also the outliers.

Here you can read more: https://towardsdatascience.com/understanding-boxplots-5e2df7bcbd51

boxplot(data$NewConfCases)

Often when looking at distribution of points, transforming the data with the log function is useful, and you can also color the points for different countries to have more information

ggplot(data, aes(log(NewConfCases+0.1), NewDeaths,)) + 
  geom_point()

boxplot(log(data$NewConfCases+0.1))

Exercise

Plot distribution of new deaths with boxplot:

boxplot(data$NewDeaths)
boxplot(log(data$NewDeaths+0.1))

Numeric Variable between groups

Those were didactic examples that however do not give us a real understanding of the data. Now we try to have a closer look at interesting things.

Histograms

One thing we can explore is the distribution of cases across different groups. Here for example we use histograms to compare today distribution of new cases across countries

length(unique(data$CountryExp))
## [1] 143
col <- topo.colors(length(unique(data$CountryExp)))
names(col) <- unique(data$CountryExp)

data$Date <- as.character(data$DateRep)

March14 <- data[which(data$Date=="2020-03-14"),]
ggplot(March14, aes(CountryExp, NewConfCases, col= col[March14$CountryExp],)) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="none")

Exercise

Analyse in a similar way the number of new deaths

March14 <- data[which(data$Date=="2020-03-14"),]
ggplot(March14, aes(CountryExp, NewDeaths, col= col[March14$CountryExp],)) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="none")

Another way to perform a similar kind of analysis is to compare distribution of new cases along time, splitting the bars for countries

ggplot(data, aes(Date, NewConfCases, fill=CountryExp)) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="bottom")

But if there are too many countries this representation is difficult to read, so we move to the next chapter:

Cases along time

One basic analysis we can do is to check the evolution of new cases along time with scatterplots.

ggplot(data, aes(x= DateRep, y= NewConfCases)) + 
  geom_point()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))

But with all the data aggregated is kind of useless, so we can split and observe the evolution in different Countries

Italy <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="Italy"),]
  p <- ggplot(Italy, aes(x= DateRep, y= NewConfCases, col= col["Italy"])) + 
    geom_point() + 
    ggtitle("Italy") +
    theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
    theme(legend.position = "none") 
  p

China <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="China"),]
  p <- ggplot(China, aes(x= DateRep, y= NewConfCases, col= col["China"])) + 
    geom_point() + 
    ggtitle("China") +
    theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
    theme(legend.position = "none") 
  p

Germany <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="Germany"),]
  p <- ggplot(Germany, aes(x= DateRep, y= NewConfCases, col= col["Germany"])) + 
    geom_point() + 
    ggtitle("Germany") +
    theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
    theme(legend.position = "none") 
  p

And now we will find a way to do the same for all the country in a fast way: (for reasons of space I will only do the loop for the first 10 countries, but you can easily change that and try it in the exercise chunk..)

for (i in unique(data$CountryExp)[1:10]) {
  tmp <- data[which(data$CountryExp==i),]
  p <- ggplot(tmp, aes(x= DateRep, y= NewConfCases, col= col[i])) + 
    geom_point() + 
    ggtitle(i) +
    theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
    theme(legend.position = "none")  
  print(p)
}

Regression

Now we perform a linear regression to follow the trend

Italy <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="Italy"),]

Italy$pred <- predict(lm(NewConfCases ~ DateRep , data = Italy))
ggplot(Italy, aes(x =DateRep, y = NewConfCases)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred)) +
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Or better fit an exponential model in this case

Italy$pred <- exp(predict(lm(log2(NewConfCases+0.01) ~ DateRep , data = Italy)))
ggplot(Italy, aes(x =DateRep, y = NewConfCases)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(aes(y = pred)) +
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Exercise

Now repeat the same analysis for the cases of new deaths along time for Germany

Germany <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="Germany"),]
Germany$pred <- exp(predict(lm(log2(NewDeaths+0.01) ~ DateRep , data = Germany)))
ggplot(Germany, aes(x =DateRep, y = NewDeaths)) +

Total Cases

Finally we compute the total number of cases for each country and look again at the data

data$totalCases <- 0
data$totalDeaths <- 0
data$totalCasesPerDay <- 0
data$totalDeathsPerDay <- 0

for (i in unique(data$CountryExp)) {
data$totalCases[which(data$CountryExp==i)] <- sum(data$NewConfCases[which(data$CountryExp==i)])  
}

ggplot(data, aes(CountryExp, totalCases, col=col[data$CountryExp])) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="none")

ggplot(data, aes(CountryExp, log(totalCases+0.1), col=col[data$CountryExp])) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="none")

And also at the evolution of total cases per day, in this case using an interactive plot, so that if you hover the mouse on the point you can check the precise values and the country.

data <- data[order(data$DateRep),]
for (i in unique(data$CountryExp)) {
  tmp <- data[which(data$CountryExp==i),]
      for (j in c(1:length(unique(tmp$Date)))) {
        
          tmp$totalCasesPerDay[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j])] <- sum(tmp$totalCasesPerDay[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j-1])] + tmp$NewConfCases[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j])])
          
      }
  data$totalCasesPerDay[which(data$CountryExp==i)] <- tmp$totalCasesPerDay
}

scatterPlot <- ggplot(data, aes(x =DateRep, y = totalCasesPerDay, text =CountryExp)) +
  geom_point(colour = col[data$CountryExp]) + 
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1)) +
  theme_classic()

ggplotly(scatterPlot)

(Remember if you want to isolate 1 country)

Italy <- data[which(data$CountryExp=="Italy"),]
ggplot(Italy, aes(x =DateRep, y = totalCasesPerDay)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Final Exercises

Analyse in a similar way the number of deaths

for (i in unique(data$CountryExp)) {
data$totalDeaths[which(data$CountryExp==i)] <- sum(data$NewDeaths[which(data$CountryExp==i)])  
}

ggplot(data, aes(CountryExp, totalDeaths, col=col[data$CountryExp])) +
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  theme(legend.position="none")
data <- data[order(data$DateRep),]
for (i in unique(data$CountryExp)) {
  tmp <- data[which(data$CountryExp==i),]
      for (j in c(1:length(unique(tmp$Date)))) {
        
          tmp$totalDeathsPerDay[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j])] <- sum(tmp$totalDeathsPerDay[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j-1])] + tmp$NewDeaths[which(tmp$Date==tmp$Date[j])])
          
      }
  data$totalDeathsPerDay[which(data$CountryExp==i)] <- tmp$totalDeathsPerDay
}

scatterPlot <- ggplot(data, aes(x =DateRep, y = totalDeathsPerDay, text =CountryExp)) +
  geom_point(colour = col[data$CountryExp]) + 
  theme(axis.text.x= element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1)) +
  theme_classic()

ggplotly(scatterPlot)
